content.description:
From the guidebook: 

  Climb the bulge right of the crack pockets-to-finger bucket-to-pockets. The high first bolt   is complimented by a sharp mono.

climbs.name: Texas Bros
climbs.fa: Kelly Elverum, Kurt Bethke, Jeff Thornton,  January 2013

content.description: Slightly overhanging face with small to medium  edges and pockets, side pulls, and a nice side/under-pull up high.  Climbers seem to agree the crux is just above the 2nd bolt.  Rock quality is good for POB.
content.location: Right of Mississippi Of Texas; just left of the arete.

content.description: Start on Pogo Factor and griddle-traverse the headwall above the cave.

Pull, get the feet up, and slap for the cool single-hand jug. Above, getting stood up on the   mini-ridge is more off-balance than it might appear? There are variants getting to the belay:   tricky bulge (up & right / 5.10b), or sidestep left (5.10a) quasi joining Pirates of the Brazos.
content.protection: 3 bolts, shares anchors with Pirates of the Brazos

content.description: From the guidebook:    Start in the corner defining the right side of the cave, but climb the gray face, left of the   upper corner.   Note: Attempts have been made to remove the unnecessary, bad (i.e., damaged) bolt on   this route the FA party has indicated that theyll get it out sooner or later?

From the guidebook:  

  Climb ground-level jugs, past thin pockets, to round hole. Thank you round-hole rest!   Continue on pleasantly awkward moves to the belay.

From the guidebook: 

  Start in the corner defining the right side of the cave, and stay in the corner above.
content.protection: 1 bolt, gear .5" to .75".  Use the tree for anchor.

content.description:
From the guidebook: 

  Climb the centerpiece black face. A superb undercling leads to gastons and edges out   right, before pulling back to center.

From the guidebook:  

  Climb the face above the ground-level hang, skirting right of the bolts, on sidepulls, and thin   pockets. A variation skirting left of the bolts will be much harder.

From the guidebook: 

  Climb the obvious jam-looking crack via mixed crack, and face maneuvers, on somewhat   sharp holds.
content.protection: Gear .5in to 3.5in, shares fixed belay with Texas Tea

content.description: Starting off of a shallow 2-finger pocket, climb the arching feature. When prudent, balance   to a stance (committing, but at least the landing is good) on top. Protect in the horizontal   crack for insurance, before topping out on jugs.
content.protection: gear 1in to 2in / 25ft / shares fixed belay with Mississippi of Texas

content.description:
From the guidebook: 

  Climb steep white rock to cool cave holds. Finish on black bulge, and pocket pulls.

On the left side of the cave, climb the horizontal fingertip rail, sloth style, to the pronounced   jug at the lip (5.11a) nothing but air. Throw the heel, and get clipped. Getting established   on the headwall (crux) is a grunt. Holds return for the upper section (5.10), but they never   seem to be in your face? This roof is reminiscent of sandstone, rather than limestone;   classic features.   Note: Sometime late summer 2005, the section of roof delineated by the fingertip rail, and   jug, a sheet approximately 4.5ft x 10ft x 10in parted from the cave (see scar, and debris),   the victim of spontaneous rock fall. Alas, one of the most unique limestone routes around   has become talus food. Hangers were pulled for reuse.
content.location: Farthest route upstream in the cave.

content.description: (12 routes & variations from 5.6 to 5.12a, 3 boulder problems from VB- to V0- / primarily   south facing)   The walls located before, and after, the big cave.
